## Policy Implications

High-frequency routes such as **{{ top_routes[0].route_short_name }}** demonstrate strong commercial viability and dense, turn-up-and-go service patterns typical of major urban corridors. Such routes are prime candidates for scrutiny under the Bus Services Act 2025's franchising provisions (cross-reference bsa1/bsa2): where a single operator controls a high-frequency, high-revenue corridor, LTAs may assess whether franchising would deliver better value or service integration than the status quo.

Low-frequency routes such as **{{ bottom_routes[0].route_short_name }}**, by contrast, often indicate marginal or lifeline services running only a handful of journeys per day. These routes warrant cross-referencing against evening-isolation and Sunday-desert findings (b2/b3) — a route running fewer than 10 trips per day is unlikely to provide meaningful evening or weekend coverage, and may be a candidate for frequency restoration under the policy scenarios modelled in this report (ps1).

This analysis covers **{{ n_routes|format_thousands }}** routes in {{ scope_label }}, ranked by daily scheduled trip count from BODS GTFS.

*Methodology: n_trips_per_day is the count of scheduled trips per route_id (GTFS route_type=3, bus only) in BODS GTFS trips.txt. route_short_name and agency_name are sourced from route_geometries.parquet (BODS routes.txt/agency.txt).*
